Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The report includes a photograph of a "goat with infected face", accompanied by the herder's remark, "Many goats have been found with infected faces which are very unusual." The picture shows highly proliferative lesions around the lips and, to a lesser extent, in the armpits. The plausible involvement of severe contagious ecthyma (orf) infection deserves to be checked. This (zoonotic) virus of small ruminants could, in severe cases, cause considerable mortality. Confirmation or otherwise, and exclusion of other clinical signs and etiologies, is anticipated.

As to cattle and buffaloes: in the absence of information on their clinical signs, gross pathological changes, and epidemiological statistics (morbidity and mortality numbers and rates), the etiology of their deaths remains to be obtained if/when veterinary investigation is carried out and becomes public.

The report covers an extended period, relating to cows and goats which "have been dying for the last 6 months"; more than a single etiology, in each of the named species, could be involved. - Mod.AS

